Anonymous Mon 29 Aug 2022 15:19:26 No.50531048 Report
Quoted By: >>50531647 >>50534899
>>50518891
A Changing Relationship has strong potential, but also a lot of problems.
I think the worldbuilding/setting is pretty cool, a human world struck by an alien mutagen that causes unlucky people to transform into anthros resembling the animals they last made contact with. I know transformation gets a bad wrap here, but I personally think it's a cool narrative element, so you have my kudos for using it pretty well. Making Jack's dad transform too was a good narrative choice that made the world feel more cohesive.
On to the bad:
The dialogue doesn't feel realistic to me, a lot of the characters speak in run on sentences that could easily be broken up with a comma or two. Past that a lot of it feels exposition heavy, and I think a fair bit of the information present can be inferred from the reading. If you find yourself repeating details between the prose and dialogue, consider cutting things down.
A more personal complaint is that I don't find the comedic elements of the story funny. Different people have different senses of humor, but there were a few scenes that I could tell were written to be comic relief, and they couldn't get a laugh out of me.
The relationship between Jack and Eevee feels really rushed, and the "they've known each other forever" handwave doesn't work for me. They decide that they're a couple after one date, which is already taking things fast (Three is standard for most people.) It's only about a week after that where she's mostly transformed and Jack declares his love for her with mock wedding vows. You can argue that they spent a lot of time together in that week because he's been playing nurse, but if that's the case the author should have written more scenes between them. I don't buy it.
I'm going to read up to chapter 6 because I do want to give this story a chance to develop. I'll give my thoughts later.
